        "*Unit root tests for log real GDP and log real consumption in levels, with a\n",
        "deterministic trend included. The ADF fails to reject the unit root null for\n",
        "both series; the KPSS rejects the null of stationarity for both. Together they\n",
        "confirm that both series are I(1), consistent with the visual evidence in\n",
        "Figure 8.1.*\n",
        "\n",
        "Second, the two series track each other closely. The log consumption series\n",
        "lies consistently below the log GDP series — consumption is a subset of output,\n",
        "so this is mechanically expected — but the vertical distance between them is\n",
        "notably stable. During recessions, when both series contract, the gap barely\n",
        "widens. During expansions, neither series pulls dramatically ahead of the other.\n",
        "This visual stability of the gap suggests that the difference between log GDP\n",
        "and log consumption — equivalently, the log of the saving rate — may itself be\n",
        "stationary, even though each series in isolation is not.\n",
        "\n",
        "This is exactly the hypothesis of cointegration: two I(1) series that share a\n",
        "common stochastic trend will have a linear combination that is I(0). Figure 8.2\n",
        "makes this concrete by plotting the log consumption-to-GDP ratio — the simplest\n",
        "candidate for such a linear combination — alongside the two individual series\n",
        "re-based to their 1947Q1 values. The levels clearly trend upward without bound;\n",
        "whether the ratio is stationary is a question the figure raises but does not\n",
        "definitively answer."
      ],
